attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, version 1 (ARM), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a self-propagating IoT worm, likely a Mirai variant. The malware attempts to spread by scanning for open Telnet ports and brute-forcing credentials using an extensive hardcoded list of common username/password pairs (e.g., root:vizxv, admin:admin, root:123456) found in function `sub_12ed0`. Upon successful login, it uses a multi-protocol downloader command (`/bin/busybox wget ... | sh`, `/bin/busybox tftp ... | sh`) to fetch and execute the next-stage payload, ensuring its propagation across vulnerable devices.
